  "prompt": "Do male dogs recognize their own puppies?",
  "response": "Male dogs generally do not recognize their own puppies. Unlike some species where fathers play an active role in parenting, male dogs typically do not have a strong paternal instinct or the ability to identify their specific offspring. In canine social structures, male dogs may interact with puppies but do not typically show special recognition or care for their biological offspring.\n\nFemale dogs, on the other hand, have a strong maternal instinct and can recognize and care for their own puppies through scent and other biological cues. Male dogs are more likely to view puppies simply as part of their pack or social group.",
